<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Fade" class="currentChild" href="Fade">Fade</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In motion picture and video production, and in audio recording, any gradual increase or decrease in the intensity of an image or signal, such as from black or silence (<a title="Fade-In" href="Fade-In">fade-in</a>), to black or silence (<a title="Fade-Out" href="Fade-Out">fade-out</a>), or to another image or audio signal (<a title="cross fade" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/cross_fade">cross fade</a> or <a title="Dissolve" href="Dissolve">dissolve</a>). The term <em>fade</em> is also used as a verb meaning to effect any of these fades. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In printing, <em>fade</em> means to reduce in intensity, such as of a printing ink, over time or upon exposure to light or other conditions. 
</p>
